english:
  title: Reply to the Lord of Tsushima
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I received your letter and learned with great joy that your health and vigor remain sound. The gifts you sent have been received with proper respect. I have considered the sentiments you expressed, and having heard the words of your envoy, I find there are certain matters that merit clarification.

    The relations between our two nations stretch back through many generations. Since the founding of our dynasty, the honored lord of your island first showed sincerity toward us. His successors maintained this devotion with utmost earnestness, yet in their final years, harmony could not be preserved. Your islanders scattered and became pirates, raiding our southern shores. Our late king, greatly angered, dispatched troops to punish this offense. For several years, contact ceased between us. When Lord Sŏngjo sent envoys to seek reconciliation and pardon, he revealed that the sea pirates were chiefly from Iki and Kyushu, not solely from your island. Our late king, hearing this, deemed it just to punish the guilty and spare the penitent—the eternal principle of governance. Since your lord had submitted, we saw no reason to dwell on past transgressions, and we ordered that you be received as before.

    From that time, envoys were sent yearly, their numbers varying. Our late king established fixed quotas for tribute ships from various provinces, yet he left yours undefined, fearing disorder might arise. In the year Kyehae, we agreed that fifty vessels would constitute your annual quota. Officials assigned to your island should know this number well, with written records to verify it. All other matters—the facilities for receiving envoys, the protocol of hospitality, the regulations of passage, the size of vessels, the number of travelers—all have been established according to custom. Each party has sworn to uphold these agreements and dare not transgress.

    It is the nature of all law that time brings decay, yet decay brings remedy—this is the ordinary course of statecraft. The journey from Sampo to our capital has a prescribed duration, yet travelers tarry at every station, sometimes losing entire seasons. Not only do your islanders seek excessive provisions; even your interpreters scheme for private gain. In recent years, calamity struck the southern provinces, harvests failed, and the coastal stations reported they could scarcely bear their obligations. We merely restated the old agreements to curtail excess and remedy these abuses—we did not alter the original compact. Indeed, we have been lenient even toward small violations and have not quibbled over them.

    Your letter claims the treatment differs from precedent—a matter I find difficult to comprehend. Regarding the grain mixed with dust and debris that your envoy mentioned: this is the fault of our border officials. Due to recent poor harvests, our tax revenues are meager, and we have been forced to use old stores. Yet surely mixing them with dust is not our nation's intent. We have now reported this matter in full to our lord.

    Our king has instructed us thus: "The Lord of Tsushima demonstrates wisdom in adapting to circumstance while maintaining principle, serving the greater realm with sincerity. All that we have advised, he hears and obeys without hesitation or doubt. He does not obstruct communication but openly shares his concerns. This I greatly commend. Let the Ministry of Rites grant his envoys five additional days for their journey, and let us punish the negligence of our border officials in providing provisions. Treat all people from Tsushima with increased generosity."

    I offer this reply with his instructions in mind. I humbly reflect that in relations between nations, we must pursue simplicity and steadfastly honor our covenants, so that neither side grows weary, and thus our friendship endures and deepens. Should each side heed every rumor and suspect the other's motives, regret will surely follow. When small-minded people lack satisfaction, they cry alarm—yet if they find no peace, how can others remain undisturbed? This is surely the path of foolishness.

    We give abundantly and receive sparingly, expending vast sums without hesitation each year. Even those unaware of the cost must see that we are depleting our stored reserves—surely not a trivial matter. Yet our lord does this because he regards your people and ours with equal compassion.

    I urge you to reflect deeply on both beginning and end, to weigh advantage and harm, and to embody our king's intention that both nations may flourish without interruption. Restrain those who would deceive, forbid transgressions, strengthen sincerity, and let our friendship endure—would this not be most fitting?

    Observing your recent conduct, I find your actions accord well with principle. You display clarity, trustworthiness, and sincerity, with nothing hidden. Truly, you are one with whom great things can be accomplished. Such meetings as this are rare; I venture to lay bare all that is in my heart. May you reflect upon these words and bring yet greater honor to our bond. This would be my deepest hope.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Tsushima Island (Tae-ma Island in Korean) lies between Japan and Korea and was a crucial point of contact between the two nations during this period.
  - key: ''
